Over 40 wells in  Naka town in Gwer West local government area of Benue State have been polluted with substances suspected to be fuel, a development that endangers the lives of several households in the area. Affected residents along Adoka -Naka road in the community called on government, security agencies, the state House of Assembly and other relevant stakeholders to come to their rescue before the situation gets out of hand. Kpejande-high-level community has more than 3000 residents, and have expressed fears that if nothing is done to address the situation the entire community may be in flames as many youths and commercial motorcyclists are scooping the suspected fuel to power their machines and vehicles. Speaking to our correspondent, the community leader, Mr Angba Francis, highlighted diverse challenges arising from the contaminated wells, one of which was their source of drinking water which had become polluted for domestic use, alleging that one fuel station in the area was responsible for the development. A resident, Mrs Terfa Mbapuun whose house was about two blocks away from the alleged fuel station said her daughter sustained minor injuries from explosion while trying to boil water fetched from the well. Speaking more on the issue, other residents, Mr Nyigba Geoffery and Gerrard Ugbede, averred they had noticed the pollution over three years ago and lodged complaints about the matter to the owner of the only filling station, the police division, and DPR, saying they didn’t get feedback and nor any serious commitment on the part of the owner whom they suspect is not doing enough to alleviate the plights of the people When contacted the owner of the filling station, Gabriel Oguche who was away in Abuja, said the underground fuel tanks have been checked for leakages but there was nothing wrong with the amenity, alleging someone may be trying to sabotage his business. He maintained the pollution of the wells was not from his station, saying, regrettably, community residents do not believe same. Meanwhile the head of Health, Safety and Environment, Department of Petroleum Resources in Makurdi, Mr Salihu Mohammad, said the department was aware of the situation but requested the community to write a formal letter to them to enable them take it up formally and carry out sample of the exact pollution in the wells.